    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Refers to either a writing table incorporating drawers or a type of case furniture, generally a chest of drawers, with a hinged, fall-front writing surface. The first furniture types to be referred to by this term developed in France in the mid-17th century, the term having evolved from the medieval French word for a coarse linen cloth that was laid on a table to provide a surface for writing.  In modern usage, in Europe a "bureau" is a writing desk, usually with a hinged writing flap that rests at a sloping angle when closed and, when opened, reveals a tier of pigeonholes, small drawers, and sometimes a small cupboard.  In the United States, a "bureau" is typically synonymous with a "chest of drawers," having lost the surface for writing.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000004401/Beard and Goodison, English Furniture (1987)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Escritorios ingleses que tienen una tapa inclinada en un ángulo agudo (normalmente 45 grados) que se dobla hacia fuera como superficie para escribir, encima de los cajones.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
